[src:spectral-theory/eigenfunction] The eigenfunctions φk of the Hamiltonian operator are stationary states of the quantum mechanical system, each with a corresponding energy Ek.
[src:spectral-theory/eigenfunction] They represent allowable energy states of the system and may be constrained by boundary conditions.
[src:spectral-theory/eigenfunction] The Hamiltonian operator H is an example of a Hermitian operator whose eigenfunctions form an orthonormal basis.
[src:spectral-theory/eigenfunction] The success of the Schrödinger equation in explaining the spectral characteristics of hydrogen is considered one of the greatest triumphs of 20th century physics.
[src:spectral-theory/eigenfunction] In the study of signals and systems, an eigenfunction of a system is a signal *f*(*t*) that, when input into the system, produces a response *y*(*t*) = *λf*(*t*), where λ is a complex scalar eigenvalue.
[src:spectral-theory/resolvent-formalism] In mathematics, the **resolvent formalism** is a technique for applying concepts from complex analysis to the study of the spectrum of operators on Banach spaces and more general spaces.
[src:spectral-theory/resolvent-formalism] Formal justification for the manipulations can be found in the framework of holomorphic functional calculus.
[src:spectral-theory/resolvent-formalism] The **resolvent** captures the spectral properties of an operator in the analytic structure of the functional.
[src:spectral-theory/resolvent-formalism] Among other uses, the resolvent may be used to solve the inhomogeneous Fredholm integral equations; a commonly used approach is a series solution, the Liouville–Neumann series.
[src:spectral-theory/resolvent-formalism] The resolvent of A can be used to directly obtain information about the spectral decomposition of A.
[src:spectral-theory/resolvent-formalism] For example, suppose λ is an isolated eigenvalue in the spectrum of A.
[src:spectral-theory/resolvent-formalism] That is, suppose there exists a simple closed curve $C_{\lambda }$ in the complex plane that separates λ from the rest of the spectrum of A.
[src:spectral-theory/resolvent-formalism] defines a projection operator onto the λ eigenspace of A.
[src:spectral-theory/resolvent-formalism] The Hille–Yosida theorem relates the resolvent through a Laplace transform to an integral over the one-parameter group of transformations generated by A.
[src:spectral-theory/resolvent-formalism] Thus, for example, if A is a skew-Hermitian matrix, then *U*(*t*) = exp(*tA*) is a one-parameter group of unitary operators.
[src:spectral-theory/resolvent-formalism] where the integral is taken along the ray $\arg t=-\arg \lambda$ .
[src:spectral-theory/resolvent-formalism] The first major use of the resolvent operator as a series in A (cf.
[src:spectral-theory/resolvent-formalism] Liouville–Neumann series) was by Ivar Fredholm, in a landmark 1903 paper in *Acta Mathematica* that helped establish modern operator theory.
[src:spectral-theory/resolvent-formalism] The name *resolvent* was given by David Hilbert.
[src:spectral-theory/resolvent-formalism] The **second resolvent identity** is a generalization of the first resolvent identity, above, useful for comparing the resolvents of two distinct operators.
[src:spectral-theory/resolvent-formalism] When studying a closed unbounded operator A: H → H on a Hilbert space H, if there exists $z\in \rho (A)$ such that $R(z;A)$ is a compact operator, we say that A has compact resolvent.
[src:spectral-theory/resolvent-formalism] The spectrum $\sigma (A)$ of such A is a discrete subset of $\mathbb {C}$ .
[src:spectral-theory/resolvent-formalism] If furthermore A is self-adjoint, then $\sigma (A)\subset \mathbb {R}$ and there exists an orthonormal basis $\{v_{i}\}_{i\in \mathbb {N} }$ of eigenvectors of A with eigenvalues $\{\lambda _{i}\}_{i\in \mathbb {N} }$ respectively.
[src:spectral-theory/resolvent-formalism] Also, $\{\lambda _{i}\}$ has no finite accumulation point.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] In mathematics, a **self-adjoint operator** on a complex vector space V with inner product $\langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle$ is a linear map A (from V to itself) that is its own adjoint.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] That is, $\langle Ax,y\rangle =\langle x,Ay\rangle$ for all $x,y\in V$ .
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] If V is finite-dimensional with a given orthonormal basis, this is equivalent to the condition that the matrix of A is a Hermitian matrix, i.e., equal to its conjugate transpose $A^{*}$ .
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] By the finite-dimensional spectral theorem, V has an orthonormal basis such that the matrix of A relative to this basis is a diagonal matrix with entries in the real numbers.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] This article deals with applying generalizations of this concept to operators on Hilbert spaces of arbitrary dimension.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Self-adjoint operators are used in functional analysis and quantum mechanics.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] In quantum mechanics their importance lies in the Dirac–von Neumann formulation of quantum mechanics, in which physical observables such as position, momentum, angular momentum and spin are represented by self-adjoint operators on a Hilbert space.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] which as an observable corresponds to the total energy of a particle of mass m in a real potential field V .
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Differential operators are an important class of unbounded operators.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] The structure of self-adjoint operators on infinite-dimensional Hilbert spaces essentially resembles the finite-dimensional case.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] That is to say, operators are self-adjoint if and only if they are unitarily equivalent to real-valued multiplication operators.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] With suitable modifications, this result can be extended to possibly unbounded operators on infinite-dimensional spaces.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Since an everywhere-defined self-adjoint operator is necessarily bounded, one needs to be more attentive to the domain issue in the unbounded case.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Let H be a Hilbert space and A an unbounded (i.e. not necessarily bounded) linear operator with a dense domain $\operatorname {Dom} A\subseteq H.$ This condition holds automatically when H is finite-dimensional since $\operatorname {Dom} A=H$ for every linear operator on a finite-dimensional space.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Let the inner product $\langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle$ be conjugate linear on the *second* argument.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] The densely defined operator A is called **symmetric** (or **Hermitian**) if $A\subseteq A^{*}$ , i.e., if $\operatorname {Dom} A\subseteq \operatorname {Dom} A^{*}$ and $Ax=A^{*}x$ for all $x\in \operatorname {Dom} A$ .
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Since $\operatorname {Dom} A^{*}\supseteq \operatorname {Dom} A$ is dense in H , symmetric operators are always closable (i.e. the closure of $G(A)$ is the graph of an operator).
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] If $A^{*}$ is a closed extension of A , the smallest closed extension $A^{**}$ of A must be contained in $A^{*}$ .
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] The densely defined operator A is called **self-adjoint** if $A=A^{*}$ , that is, if and only if A is symmetric and $\operatorname {Dom} A=\operatorname {Dom} A^{*}$ .
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Equivalently, a closed symmetric operator A is self-adjoint if and only if $A^{*}$ is symmetric.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] A symmetric operator A is said to be **essentially self-adjoint** if the closure of A is self-adjoint.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Equivalently, A is essentially self-adjoint if it has a *unique* self-adjoint extension.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] In practical terms, having an essentially self-adjoint operator is almost as good as having a self-adjoint operator, since we merely need to take the closure to obtain a self-adjoint operator.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] In physics, the term **Hermitian** refers to symmetric as well as self-adjoint operators alike.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] The subtle difference between the two is generally overlooked.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Let H be a Hilbert space and $A:\operatorname {Dom} (A)\to H$ a symmetric operator.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] According to Hellinger–Toeplitz theorem, if $\operatorname {Dom} (A)=H$ then A is necessarily bounded.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Every bounded operator $T:H\to H$ can be written in the complex form $T=A+iB$ where $A:H\to H$ and $B:H\to H$ are bounded self-adjoint operators.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Alternatively, every positive bounded linear operator $A:H\to H$ is self-adjoint if the Hilbert space H is *complex*.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Bounded self-adjoint operators do not necessarily have an eigenvalue.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] If, however, A is a compact self-adjoint operator then it always has an eigenvalue $|\lambda |=\|A\|$ and corresponding normalized eigenvector.
