[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] In finite dimensions, $\sigma (A)\subseteq \mathbb {C}$ consists exclusively of (complex) eigenvalues.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] The spectrum of a self-adjoint operator is always real (i.e. $\sigma (A)\subseteq \mathbb {R}$ ), though non-self-adjoint operators with real spectrum exist as well.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] For bounded (normal) operators, however, the spectrum is real *if and only if* the operator is self-adjoint.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] This implies, for example, that a non-self-adjoint operator with real spectrum is necessarily unbounded.
