[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] That is to say, the domain of the closure has the same boundary conditions as the domain of *A* itself, just a less stringent smoothness assumption.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Meanwhile, since there are "too many" boundary conditions on *A*, there are "too few" (actually, none at all in this case) for $A^{*}$ .
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] If we compute $\langle g,Af\rangle$ for $f\in \operatorname {Dom} (A)$ using integration by parts, then since f vanishes at both ends of the interval, no boundary conditions on g are needed to cancel out the boundary terms in the integration by parts.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Thus, any sufficiently smooth function g is in the domain of $A^{*}$ , with $A^{*}g=-i\,dg/dx$ .
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Since the domain of the closure and the domain of the adjoint do not agree, *A* is not essentially self-adjoint.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] After all, a general result says that the domain of the adjoint of $A^{\mathrm {cl} }$ is the same as the domain of the adjoint of *A*.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Thus, in this case, the domain of the adjoint of $A^{\mathrm {cl} }$ is bigger than the domain of $A^{\mathrm {cl} }$ itself, showing that $A^{\mathrm {cl} }$ is not self-adjoint, which by definition means that *A* is not essentially self-adjoint.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] The problem with the preceding example is that we imposed too many boundary conditions on the domain of *A*.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] With this domain, *A* is essentially self-adjoint.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] In this case, we can understand the implications of the domain issues for the spectral theorem.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] If we use the first choice of domain (with no boundary conditions), all functions $f_{\beta }(x)=e^{\beta x}$ for $\beta \in \mathbb {C}$ are eigenvectors, with eigenvalues $-i\beta$ , and so the spectrum is the whole complex plane.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] If we use the second choice of domain (with Dirichlet boundary conditions), *A* has no eigenvectors at all.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] If we use the third choice of domain (with periodic boundary conditions), we can find an orthonormal basis of eigenvectors for *A*, the functions $f_{n}(x):=e^{2\pi inx}$ .
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] Thus, in this case finding a domain such that *A* is self-adjoint is a compromise: the domain has to be small enough so that *A* is symmetric, but large enough so that $D(A^{*})=D(A)$ .
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] A more subtle example of the distinction between symmetric and (essentially) self-adjoint operators comes from Schrödinger operators in quantum mechanics.
[src:spectral-theory/self-adjoint-operator] If the potential energy is singular—particularly if the potential is unbounded below—the associated Schrödinger operator may fail to be essentially self-adjoint.
