[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] In linear algebra and functional analysis, a **spectral theorem** is a result about when a linear operator or matrix can be diagonalized (that is, represented as a diagonal matrix in some basis).
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] This is extremely useful because computations involving a diagonalizable matrix can often be reduced to much simpler computations involving the corresponding diagonal matrix of eigenvalues.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] The concept of diagonalization is relatively straightforward for operators on finite-dimensional vector spaces but requires some modification for operators on infinite-dimensional spaces.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] In general, the spectral theorem identifies a class of linear operators that can be modeled by multiplication operators, which are as simple as one can hope to find.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] In more abstract language, the spectral theorem is a statement about commutative C*-algebras.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] See also spectral theory for a historical perspective.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Examples of operators to which the spectral theorem applies are self-adjoint operators or more generally normal operators on Hilbert spaces.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] The spectral theorem also provides a canonical decomposition, called the **spectral decomposition**, of the underlying vector space on which the operator acts.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Augustin-Louis Cauchy proved the spectral theorem for symmetric matrices, i.e., that every real, symmetric matrix is diagonalizable.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] In addition, Cauchy was the first to be systematic about determinants.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] The spectral theorem as generalized by John von Neumann is today perhaps the most important result of operator theory.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] This article mainly focuses on the simplest kind of spectral theorem, that for a self-adjoint operator on a Hilbert space.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] However, as noted above, the spectral theorem also holds for normal operators on a Hilbert space.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] We begin by considering a Hermitian matrix on $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ (but the following discussion will be adaptable to the more restrictive case of symmetric matrices on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ).
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] We consider a Hermitian map *A* on a finite-dimensional complex inner product space *V* endowed with a positive definite sesquilinear inner product $\langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle$ .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] An equivalent condition is that *A** = *A*, where *A** is the Hermitian conjugate of *A*.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] In the case that *A* is identified with a Hermitian matrix, the matrix of *A** is equal to its conjugate transpose.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] This condition implies that all eigenvalues of a Hermitian map are real: To see this, it is enough to apply it to the case when *x* = *y* is an eigenvector.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] (Recall that an eigenvector of a linear map *A* is a non-zero vector *v* such that *Av* = *λv* for some scalar *λ*.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] The value *λ* is the corresponding eigenvalue.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] We provide a sketch of a proof for the case where the underlying field of scalars is the complex numbers.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] By the fundamental theorem of algebra, applied to the characteristic polynomial of *A*, there is at least one complex eigenvalue *λ*1 and corresponding eigenvector *v*1, which must by definition be non-zero.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] By Hermiticity, ${\mathcal {K}}^{n-1}$ is an invariant subspace of *A*.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] To satisfy invariance, we need to check if $A(k)\in {\mathcal {K}}^{n-1}$ .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Applying the same argument to ${\mathcal {K}}^{n-1}$ shows that *A* has at least one real eigenvalue $\lambda _{2}$ and corresponding eigenvector $v_{2}\in {\mathcal {K}}^{n-1}\perp v_{1}$ .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Finite induction then finishes the proof.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] The matrix representation of *A* in a basis of eigenvectors is diagonal, and by the construction the proof gives a basis of mutually orthogonal eigenvectors; by choosing them to be unit vectors one obtains an orthonormal basis of eigenvectors.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] *A* can be written as a linear combination of pairwise orthogonal projections, called its **spectral decomposition**.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Let $V_{\lambda }=\{v\in V:Av=\lambda v\}$ be the eigenspace corresponding to an eigenvalue $\lambda$ .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Note that the definition does not depend on any choice of specific eigenvectors.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] In general, *V* is the orthogonal direct sum of the spaces $V_{\lambda }$ where the $\lambda$ ranges over the spectrum of A .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] When the matrix being decomposed is Hermitian, the spectral decomposition is a special case of the Schur decomposition (see the proof in case of normal matrices below).
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] The diagonal entries of $\Sigma$ are uniquely determined by A and are known as the singular values of A .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] The spectral theorem extends to a more general class of matrices.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Let *A* be an operator on a finite-dimensional inner product space.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] *A* is said to be normal if *A***A* = *AA**.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] One can show that *A* is normal if and only if it is unitarily diagonalizable using the Schur decomposition.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] That is, any matrix can be written as *A* = *UTU**, where *U* is unitary and *T* is upper triangular.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] If *A* is normal, then one sees that *TT** = *T***T*.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Therefore, *T* must be diagonal since a normal upper triangular matrix is diagonal (see normal matrix).
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] In other words, *A* is normal if and only if there exists a unitary matrix *U* such that $A=UDU^{*},$ where *D* is a diagonal matrix.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Then, the entries of the diagonal of *D* are the eigenvalues of *A*.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] The column vectors of *U* are the eigenvectors of *A* and they are orthonormal.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Unlike the Hermitian case, the entries of *D* need not be real.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] In the more general setting of Hilbert spaces, which may have an infinite dimension, the statement of the spectral theorem for compact self-adjoint operators is virtually the same as in the finite-dimensional case.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] As for Hermitian matrices, the key point is to prove the existence of at least one nonzero eigenvector.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] One cannot rely on determinants to show existence of eigenvalues, but one can use a maximization argument analogous to the variational characterization of eigenvalues.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] If the compactness assumption is removed, then it is *not* true that every self-adjoint operator has eigenvectors; see #Possible absence of eigenvectors.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] The next generalization we consider is that of bounded self-adjoint operators on a Hilbert space.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] This operator does not have any eigenvectors *in* $L^{2}([0,1])$ .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] However, its spectrum, suitably defined, is still equal to $[0,1]$ , see spectrum of bounded operator.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] It does also have eigenvectors in a larger space.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Namely the distribution $f(t)=\delta (t-t_{0})$ , where $\delta$ is the Dirac delta function, is an eigenvector when construed in an appropriate sense.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] The Dirac delta function is however not a function in the classical sense and does not lie in the Hilbert space *L*2[0, 1].
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Thus, the delta-functions are "generalized eigenvectors" of A but not eigenvectors in the usual sense.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] In the absence of (true) eigenvectors, one can look for a "spectral subspace" consisting of an *almost eigenvector*, i.e., a closed subspace $V_{E}$ of V associated with a Borel set $E\subset \sigma (A)$ in the spectrum of A .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] This subspace can be thought of as the closed span of generalized eigenvectors for A with eigen*values* in E .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] In the above example, where $[Af](t)=tf(t),\;$ we might consider the subspace of functions supported on a small interval $[a,a+\varepsilon ]$ inside $[0,1]$ .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] This space is invariant under A and for any f in this subspace, $Af$ is very close to $af$ .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Each subspace, in turn, is encoded by the associated projection operator, and the collection of all the subspaces is then represented by a projection-valued measure.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] An alternative formulation of the spectral theorem says that every bounded self-adjoint operator is unitarily equivalent to a multiplication operator, a relatively simple type of operator.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Multiplication operators are a direct generalization of diagonal matrices.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] A finite-dimensional Hermitian vector space V may be coordinatized as the space of functions $f:B\to \mathbb {C}$ from a basis B to the complex numbers, so that the B -coordinates of a vector are the values of the corresponding function f .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Also A is unitarily equivalent to the multiplication operator $[Tf](v)=\lambda (v)f(v)$ , where $\lambda (v)$ is the eigenvalue of $v\in B$ : that is, A multiplies each B -coordinate by the corresponding eigenvalue $\lambda (v)$ , the action of a diagonal matrix.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Finally, the operator norm $|A|=|T|$ is equal to the magnitude of the largest eigenvalue $|\lambda |_{\infty }$ .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] The spectral theorem is the beginning of the vast research area of functional analysis called operator theory; see also spectral measure.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] There is also an analogous spectral theorem for bounded normal operators on Hilbert spaces.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] The only difference in the conclusion is that now *$\lambda$* may be complex-valued.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] There is also a formulation of the spectral theorem in terms of direct integrals.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] It is similar to the multiplication-operator formulation, but more canonical.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Let A be a bounded self-adjoint operator and let $\sigma (A)$ be the spectrum of A .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] The direct-integral formulation of the spectral theorem associates two quantities to A .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] The spaces $H_{\lambda }$ can be thought of as something like "eigenspaces" for A .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Note, however, that unless the one-element set $\lambda$ has positive measure, the space $H_{\lambda }$ is not actually a subspace of the direct integral.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Thus, the $H_{\lambda }$ 's should be thought of as "generalized eigenspace"—that is, the elements of $H_{\lambda }$ are "eigenvectors" that do not actually belong to the Hilbert space.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Although both the multiplication-operator and direct integral formulations of the spectral theorem express a self-adjoint operator as unitarily equivalent to a multiplication operator, the direct integral approach is more canonical.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] First, the set over which the direct integral takes place (the spectrum of the operator) is canonical.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Second, the function we are multiplying by is canonical in the direct-integral approach: Simply the function $\lambda \mapsto \lambda$ .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] A vector $\varphi$ is called a cyclic vector for A if the vectors $\varphi ,A\varphi ,A^{2}\varphi ,\ldots$ span a dense subspace of the Hilbert space.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Suppose A is a bounded self-adjoint operator for which a cyclic vector exists.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] In that case, there is no distinction between the direct-integral and multiplication-operator formulations of the spectral theorem.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Indeed, in that case, there is a measure $\mu$ on the spectrum $\sigma (A)$ of A such that A is unitarily equivalent to the "multiplication by $\lambda$ " operator on $L^{2}(\sigma (A),\mu )$ .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] This result represents A simultaneously as a multiplication operator *and* as a direct integral, since $L^{2}(\sigma (A),\mu )$ is just a direct integral in which each Hilbert space $H_{\lambda }$ is just $\mathbb {C}$ .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Not every bounded self-adjoint operator admits a cyclic vector; indeed, by the uniqueness in the direct integral decomposition, this can occur only when all the $H_{\lambda }$ 's have dimension one.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] When this happens, we say that A has "simple spectrum" in the sense of spectral multiplicity theory.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] That is, a bounded self-adjoint operator that admits a cyclic vector should be thought of as the infinite-dimensional generalization of a self-adjoint matrix with distinct eigenvalues (i.e., each eigenvalue has multiplicity one).
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Although not every A admits a cyclic vector, it is easy to see that we can decompose the Hilbert space as a direct sum of invariant subspaces on which A has a cyclic vector.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] This observation is the key to the proofs of the multiplication-operator and direct-integral forms of the spectral theorem.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] One important application of the spectral theorem (in whatever form) is the idea of defining a functional calculus.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] That is, given a function f defined on the spectrum of A , we wish to define an operator $f(A)$ .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] If f is simply a positive power, $f(x)=x^{n}$ , then $f(A)$ is just the n -th power of A , $A^{n}$ .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] The interesting cases are where f is a nonpolynomial function such as a square root or an exponential.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Either of the versions of the spectral theorem provides such a functional calculus.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Many important linear operators which occur in analysis, such as differential operators, are unbounded.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] There is also a spectral theorem for self-adjoint operators that applies in these cases.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] To give an example, every constant-coefficient differential operator is unitarily equivalent to a multiplication operator.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Indeed, the unitary operator that implements this equivalence is the Fourier transform; the multiplication operator is a type of Fourier multiplier.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] In general, spectral theorem for self-adjoint operators may take several equivalent forms.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Specifically, the only reason the multiplication operator A on $L^{2}([0,1])$ is bounded, is due to the choice of domain $[0,1]$ .
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] The same operator on, e.g., $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ would be unbounded.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] The notion of "generalized eigenvectors" naturally extends to unbounded self-adjoint operators, as they are characterized as non-normalizable eigenvectors.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Contrary to the case of almost eigenvectors, however, the eigenvalues can be real or complex and, even if they are real, do not necessarily belong to the spectrum.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theorem] Though, for self-adjoint operators there always exist a real subset of "generalized eigenvalues" such that the corresponding set of eigenvectors is complete.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] In mathematics, **spectral theory** is an inclusive term for theories extending the eigenvector and eigenvalue theory of a single square matrix to a much broader theory of the structure of operators in a variety of mathematical spaces.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] It is a result of studies of linear algebra and the solutions of systems of linear equations and their generalizations.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] The theory is connected to that of analytic functions because the spectral properties of an operator are related to analytic functions of the spectral parameter.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] The name *spectral theory* was introduced by David Hilbert in his original formulation of Hilbert space theory, which was cast in terms of quadratic forms in infinitely many variables.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] The original spectral theorem was therefore conceived as a version of the theorem on principal axes of an ellipsoid, in an infinite-dimensional setting.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] The later discovery in quantum mechanics that spectral theory could explain features of atomic spectra was therefore fortuitous.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] There have been three main ways to formulate spectral theory, each of which find use in different domains.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] After Hilbert's initial formulation, the later development of abstract Hilbert spaces and the spectral theory of single normal operators on them were well suited to the requirements of physics, exemplified by the work of von Neumann.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] The further theory built on this to address Banach algebras in general.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] This development leads to the Gelfand representation, which covers the commutative case, and further into non-commutative harmonic analysis.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] The difference can be seen in making the connection with Fourier analysis.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] The Fourier transform on the real line is in one sense the spectral theory of differentiation as a differential operator.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] But for that to cover the phenomena one has already to deal with generalized eigenfunctions (for example, by means of a rigged Hilbert space).
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] On the other hand, it is simple to construct a group algebra, the spectrum of which captures the Fourier transform's basic properties, and this is carried out by means of Pontryagin duality.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] One can also study the spectral properties of operators on Banach spaces.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] For example, compact operators on Banach spaces have many spectral properties similar to that of matrices.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] Such physical ideas have nothing to do with the mathematical theory on a technical level, but there are examples of indirect involvement (see for example Mark Kac's question *Can you hear the shape of a drum?*).
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] Hilbert's adoption of the term "spectrum" has been attributed to an 1897 paper of Wilhelm Wirtinger on Hill differential equation (by Jean Dieudonné), and it was taken up by his students during the first decade of the twentieth century, among them Erhard Schmidt and Hermann Weyl.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] The conceptual basis for Hilbert space was developed from Hilbert's ideas by Erhard Schmidt and Frigyes Riesz.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] The later discovery in quantum mechanics that spectral theory could explain features of atomic spectra was therefore fortuitous, rather than being an object of Hilbert's spectral theory.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] Consider a bounded linear transformation *T* defined everywhere over a general Banach space.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] Here *I* is the identity operator and ζ is a complex number.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] If the inverse exists, *T* is called *regular*.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] If it does not exist, *T* is called *singular*.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] With these definitions, the *resolvent set* of *T* is the set of all complex numbers ζ such that *Rζ* exists and is bounded.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] The *spectrum* of *T* is the set of all complex numbers ζ such that *Rζ* fails to exist or is unbounded.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] Often the spectrum of *T* is denoted by *σ*(*T*).
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] The function *Rζ* for all ζ in *ρ*(*T*) (that is, wherever *Rζ* exists as a bounded operator) is called the resolvent of *T*.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] The *spectrum* of *T* is therefore the complement of the *resolvent set* of *T* in the complex plane.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] Every eigenvalue of *T* belongs to *σ*(*T*), but *σ*(*T*) may contain non-eigenvalues.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] This definition applies to a Banach space, but of course other types of space exist as well; for example, topological vector spaces include Banach spaces, but can be more general.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] On the other hand, Banach spaces include Hilbert spaces, and it is these spaces that find the greatest application and the richest theoretical results.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] With suitable restrictions, much can be said about the structure of the spectra of transformations in a Hilbert space.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] In particular, for self-adjoint operators, the spectrum lies on the real line and (in general) is a spectral combination of a point spectrum of discrete eigenvalues and a continuous spectrum.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] In functional analysis and linear algebra the spectral theorem establishes conditions under which an operator can be expressed in simple form as a sum of simpler operators.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] As a full rigorous presentation is not appropriate for this article, we take an approach that avoids much of the rigor and satisfaction of a formal treatment with the aim of being more comprehensible to a non-specialist.
[src:spectral-theory/spectral-theory] This topic is easiest to describe by introducing the bra–ket notation of Dirac for operators.
