[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] In mathematics, particularly in functional analysis, the **spectrum** of a bounded linear operator (or, more generally, an unbounded linear operator) is a generalisation of the set of eigenvalues of a matrix.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] By the closed graph theorem, $\lambda$ is in the spectrum if and only if the bounded operator $T-\lambda I:V\to V$ is non-bijective on V .
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] The study of spectra and related properties is known as *spectral theory*, which has numerous applications, most notably the mathematical formulation of quantum mechanics.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] The spectrum of an operator on a finite-dimensional vector space is precisely the set of eigenvalues.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] However an operator on an infinite-dimensional space may have additional elements in its spectrum, and may have no eigenvalues.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] This has no eigenvalues, since if *Rx*=*λx* then by expanding this expression we see that *x*1=0, *x*2=0, etc.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] On the other hand, 0 is in the spectrum because although the operator *R* − 0 (i.e.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] *R* itself) is invertible, the inverse is defined on a set which is not dense in ℓ2.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] In fact *every* bounded linear operator on a complex Banach space must have a non-empty spectrum.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] The notion of spectrum extends to unbounded (i.e. not necessarily bounded) operators.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] The space of bounded linear operators *B*(*X*) on a Banach space *X* is an example of a unital Banach algebra.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] Since the definition of the spectrum does not mention any properties of *B*(*X*) except those that any such algebra has, the notion of a spectrum may be generalised to this context by using the same definition verbatim.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] Let T be a bounded linear operator acting on a Banach space X over the complex scalar field $\mathbb {C}$ , and I be the identity operator on X .
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] The **spectrum** of T is the set of all $\lambda \in \mathbb {C}$ for which the operator $T-\lambda I$ does not have an inverse that is a bounded linear operator.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] Since $T-\lambda I$ is a linear operator, the inverse is linear if it exists; and, by the bounded inverse theorem, it is bounded.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] Therefore, the spectrum consists precisely of those scalars $\lambda$ for which $T-\lambda I$ is not bijective.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] The spectrum of a given operator T is often denoted $\sigma (T)$ , and its complement, the resolvent set, is denoted $\rho (T)=\mathbb {C} \setminus \sigma (T)$ .
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] If $\lambda$ is an eigenvalue of T , then the operator $T-\lambda I$ is not one-to-one, and therefore its inverse $(T-\lambda I)^{-1}$ is not defined.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] However, the converse statement is not true: the operator $T-\lambda I$ may not have an inverse, even if $\lambda$ is not an eigenvalue.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] Thus the spectrum of an operator always contains all its eigenvalues, but is not limited to them.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] The bilateral shift operator T simply displaces every element of the sequence by one position; namely if $u=T(v)$ then $u_{i}=v_{i-1}$ for every integer i .
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] However, the operator $T-\lambda I$ is not invertible if $|\lambda |=1$ .
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] The spectrum of a bounded operator T is always a closed, bounded subset of the complex plane.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] would be defined everywhere on the complex plane and bounded.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] But it can be shown that the resolvent function R is holomorphic on its domain.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] By the vector-valued version of Liouville's theorem, this function is constant, thus everywhere zero as it is zero at infinity.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] The boundedness of the spectrum follows from the Neumann series expansion in $\lambda$ ; the spectrum $\sigma (T)$ is bounded by $\left\|T\right\|$ .
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] A similar result shows the closedness of the spectrum.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] The bound $\left\|T\right\|$ on the spectrum can be refined somewhat.
[src:spectral-theory/spectrum-functional-analysis] The *spectral radius*, $r(T)$ , of T is the radius of the smallest circle in the complex plane which is centered at the origin and contains the spectrum $\sigma (T)$ inside of it, i.e.
